onnecting to Bluetooth Module

1. ### FTDI Connection
  <p>Plug the Arduino Pro Mini into laptop using an FTDI Cable/Adapter</p>
  <p>Program following code into Arduino over serial connection</p>

  <pre><code>
   /**********************
   Bluetooth test program
   **********************/

   #include SD.h

   int counter = 0;
   int incomingByte;

   void setup() {
        Serial.begin(115200);
   }

   void loop() {
        //see if there's incoming serial data:
        if (Serial.available() > 0) {
                // read the oldest byte in the serial buffer:
                incomingByte = Serial.read();
                // if it's a capital R, reset the counter
                if (incomingByte == 'R') {
                        Serial.println("RESET");
                        counter=0;
                }
        }
        Serial.println(counter);
        counter++;

        delay(250);
   }</code></pre>

1. ### Connect Arduino to Bluetooth Mate
  <p>Attach external power to RAW/VCC pin <br />
     RAW pin use for unregulated voltages up to 12 V<br />
     VCC pin use for regulated voltage of 3.3 V</p>

  <p>Attach Bluetooth Mate to Android</p>

  <p>Turn on power supply</p>

1. ### Pair Bluetooth with Computer
  <p>Setup Bluetooth device<br />
     Under passcode options, select "Do not use a passcode for this device"<br />
     Setup a serial port for device "Edit Serial Ports"</p>

  <p>Open serial connection with device using serial communication program (PUTY, Kermit, ect.)</p>

  <p>If device is busy use <code>fuser</code> command followed by port it's being applied to to view other processes utilizing port.</p>

  <p>Processes utilizing that port can then be killed using <code>kill</code> command.</p>
    
